          <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
          <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
      <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
      <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
          <p>Illinois Tool Works generated <strong>${(fcf2025 / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, including capital expenditures required to maintain its operations.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
          <p>We grow FCF at <strong>5% per year</strong> for 5 years. ITW is a highly diversified, mature industrial company. While it executes well operationally and typically expands margins over time, top-line growth is generally tied to moderate GDP expansion and targeted acquisitions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
          <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2.5% forever</strong> — slightly below long-term GDP growth. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate). This captures all value from Year 6 to infinity.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
          <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>8.5%</strong> — our required rate of return. This reflects a baseline rate (the 10Y Treasury is currently 4.18%) plus a risk premium suited for a stable, dividend-paying industrial conglomerate.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">5</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
          <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(2)}B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString()} million) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
      <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
      <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

      <div class="assumption-grid">
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
          <div class="value">5%</div>
          <div class="rationale">
            ITW is an industrial giant with an extensive portfolio spanning automotive OEM, food equipment, testing, and polymers. They grow mostly via modest volume increases, pricing power, and operational efficiency (their "80/20 Front-to-Back" process). 5% is a reasonable expectation for a mature leader in cyclical markets.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
          <div class="value">8.5%</div>
          <div class="rationale">
            The 10Y Treasury stands at 4.18%. ITW is exceptionally stable, carrying a strong credit rating and a long history of dividend increases. Because its risk profile is lower than highly volatile tech stocks or turnaround plays, an 8.5% discount rate provides an adequate margin for investors.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
          <div class="value">2.5%</div>
          <div class="rationale">
            We model long-term growth slightly below typical nominal global GDP growth. A company of ITW's scale cannot outpace global economic growth indefinitely. 2.5% accounts for standard inflation and very mild, steady real growth in perpetuity.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
      <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
              <th>FCF ($M)</th>
              <th>PV Factor</th>
              <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
              <td>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
              <td>—</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            {projectedFCF.map(p => (
              <tr>
                <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
                <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
                <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
                <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="row-total">
              <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
              <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
      <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
              <th>Value ($M)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.025)</td>
              <td>${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (8.5% − 2.5%))</td>
              <td>${Math.round(terminalValue).toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="row-total">
              <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
      <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
              <th>Value ($M)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
              <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
              <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>+ Net Cash (Cash − Debt)</td>
              <td>${netCash.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>= Equity Value</td>
              <td>${equityValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
              <td>{sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="row-total">
              <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
              <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ HISTORICAL CHARTS ═══ -->
      <h2>Financial Track Record</h2>
      <p>Before trusting a forward projection, look at where the company has been.</p>

      <h3>Revenue ($M)</h3>
      <div class="bar-chart">
        {revChart.map(r => (
          <div class="bar-row">
            <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
            <div class="bar-track">
              <div class="bar-fill revenue" style={`width: ${(r.value !== null ? (r.value / maxRev) * 100 : 0)}%`}>
                ${r.value !== null ? r.value.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <h3>Free Cash Flow ($M)</h3>
      <div class="bar-chart">
        {fcfChart.map(r => (
          <div class="bar-row">
            <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
            <div class="bar-track">
              <div class="bar-fill fcf" style={`width: ${(r.value !== null ? (r.value / maxFcf) * 100 : 0)}%`}>
                ${r.value !== null ? r.value.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <h3>Earnings Per Share (Diluted)</h3>
      <div class="bar-chart">
        {epsChart.map(r => (
          <div class="bar-row">
            <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
            <div class="bar-track">
              <div class="bar-fill eps" style={`width: ${(r.value !== null ? (r.value / maxEps) * 100 : 0)}%`}>
                ${r.value !== null ? r.value.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ MARGIN TRENDS ═══ -->
      <h3>Margin Trends</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
              <th>Operating Margin</th>
              <th>Profit Margin</th>
              <th>FCF Margin</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {[...marginHistory].reverse().map(m => (
              <tr>
                <td>{m.year}</td>
                <td>{m.operating !== null ? m.operating + '%' : 'N/A'}</td>
                <td>{m.profit !== null ? m.profit + '%' : 'N/A'}</td>
                <td>{m.fcfMargin !== null ? m.fcfMargin + '%' : 'N/A'}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p><strong>Key observation:</strong> ITW consistently maintains robust margins. Their "80/20" operating philosophy ensures they focus primarily on their most profitable product lines, allowing them to sustain high margins even during periods of stagnant top-line growth.</p>

      <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
      <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
      <p>Our base case uses 5% growth and an 8.5% discount rate. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions.</p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="sensitivity-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
              {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
                <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
              ))}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
              <tr>
                <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
                {row.values.map((v, i) => (
                  <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                    ${v}
                  </td>
                ))}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
      <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
      <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

      <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Successful Acquisitions:</strong> ITW frequently acquires smaller, complementary businesses. If they successfully integrate new acquisitions at highly accretive margins, top-line and FCF growth could exceed the 5% assumption.</li>
        <li><strong>Aggressive Share Buybacks:</strong> ITW returns a significant amount of cash to shareholders through buybacks. Fewer outstanding shares in the future mean a higher value per share, which static DCFs under-represent.</li>
        <li><strong>Macroeconomic Boom:</strong> As an industrial conglomerate, ITW would heavily benefit from broad, sustained economic expansions or massive infrastructure spending tailwinds.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cyclical Downturns:</strong> ITW has exposure to cyclical markets (e.g., automotive, welding). A severe global recession would compress both top-line revenue and operating margins, breaking the 5% growth assumption.</li>
        <li><strong>Supply Chain Disruptions:</strong> Heavy reliance on raw materials makes them susceptible to input cost inflation and prolonged supply chain logjams, which can eat into their stellar operating margins.</li>
        <li><strong>Currency Headwinds:</strong> As a global enterprise, ITW is exposed to foreign exchange fluctuations. A persistently strong US Dollar hurts reported revenues and cash flows.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Why an 8.5% discount rate?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. With the 10-year Treasury yielding 4.18%, an 8.5% WACC builds in an equity risk premium suitable for a high-quality, dividend-growing, blue-chip industrial.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Why assume only 5% growth for a great company?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Quality does not equal rapid growth. ITW generates fantastic returns on capital, but it operates in mature markets. Significant double-digit top-line growth is highly unlikely given the size and nature of its end markets. The value lies in its consistent profitability, not explosive expansion.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, and conviction in the assumptions.</div>
        </details>
      </div>

